======================================================================
PART 1: THE MODULAR GROUP SL(2,Z)
======================================================================

SL(2,Z) is generated by S = [[0,-1],[1,0]] and T = [[1,1],[0,1]].
Our transfer matrix at x=-1: M = [[1,-1],[1,0]] = T^{-1}S (conjugate).

T^(-1)·S = [[-1, -1], [1, 0]]
M(-1) = [[1, -1], [1, 0]]
Match: False

Orders of key elements in SL(2,Z):
  S: order 4
  T: order > 19 (infinite)
  M(-1)=T^(-1)S: order 6
  ST: order 6
  TS: order 6

======================================================================
PART 2: TOURNAMENT TRANSFER MATRIX M(2) = [[1,2],[1,0]] MOD p
======================================================================

det(M(2)) = -2. So M(2) ∉ SL(2,Z), but M(2) ∈ GL(2,Z).
Modular order of M(2) mod p:
  p=  2: order(M mod p) = N/A , Jacobsthal Pisano = N/A
  p=  3: order(M mod p) =    6, Jacobsthal Pisano = 6
  p=  5: order(M mod p) =    4, Jacobsthal Pisano = 4
  p=  7: order(M mod p) =    6, Jacobsthal Pisano = 6
  p= 11: order(M mod p) =   10, Jacobsthal Pisano = 10
  p= 13: order(M mod p) =   12, Jacobsthal Pisano = 12
  p= 17: order(M mod p) =    8, Jacobsthal Pisano = 8
  p= 19: order(M mod p) =   18, Jacobsthal Pisano = 18
  p= 23: order(M mod p) =   22, Jacobsthal Pisano = 22
  p= 29: order(M mod p) =   28, Jacobsthal Pisano = 28
  p= 31: order(M mod p) =   10, Jacobsthal Pisano = 10
  p= 37: order(M mod p) =   36, Jacobsthal Pisano = 36
  p= 41: order(M mod p) =   20, Jacobsthal Pisano = 20
  p= 43: order(M mod p) =   14, Jacobsthal Pisano = 14
  p= 47: order(M mod p) =   46, Jacobsthal Pisano = 46

======================================================================
PART 3: WHY PERIOD 6 FOR MOD 3 AND MOD 7?
======================================================================

At mod 3: 2 ≡ -1, so M(2) mod 3 = M(-1) mod 3 = SL(2,Z₃) element of order 6!

Verification:
  M(2) mod 3 = [[1, 2], [1, 0]]
  M(-1) mod 3 = [[1, 2], [1, 0]]
  Equal: True

★ THIS IS THE DEEP REASON: modular 3 conflates x=2 and x=-1!
  The TOPOLOGICAL period-6 (x=-1) and the TOURNAMENT period-6 (x=2 mod 3)
  are THE SAME THING seen through the mod-3 lens!

At mod 7: 2 mod 7 = 2. Let's check the characteristic polynomial of M mod 7.
  M = [[1,2],[1,0]], char poly = λ² - λ - 2 = (λ-2)(λ+1)
  Eigenvalues mod 7: λ=2 and λ=-1≡6 mod 7
  Order of 2 in (Z/7Z)*: 3
  Order of -1 in (Z/7Z)*: 2
  LCM(order(2), order(-1)) in (Z/7Z)* = LCM(3, 2) = 6
  So M^6 ≡ diag(2^6, (-1)^6) ≡ diag(1, 1) ≡ I mod 7

★ GENERAL THEORY:
  order(M(x) mod p) = LCM(order(λ+), order(λ-)) in (Z/pZ)*
  For M(2): eigenvalues 2 and -1
  order mod p = LCM(ord_p(2), ord_p(-1)) = LCM(ord_p(2), 2)

  p  ord_p(2)  ord_p(-1)  LCM  order(M)
    3       2          2      2       6  ✗
    5       4          2      4       4  ✓
    7       3          2      6       6  ✓
   11      10          2     10      10  ✓
   13      12          2     12      12  ✓
   17       8          2      8       8  ✓
   19      18          2     18      18  ✓
   23      11          2     22      22  ✓
   29      28          2     28      28  ✓
   31       5          2     10      10  ✓
   37      36          2     36      36  ✓
   41      20          2     20      20  ✓
   43      14          2     14      14  ✓
   47      23          2     46      46  ✓

======================================================================
PART 4: THE α₂ SPECTRUM — WHY α₂=3 IS MISSING AT n=6
======================================================================

From n6_topology_fast_87.py:
  α₂ values at n=6: {0, 1, 2, 4}
  α₂=3 is MISSING!

α₂ counts independent PAIRS of odd cycles in Ω(T).
At n=6, odd cycles have length 3 or 5.
Two 3-cycles can be disjoint only if they use all 6 vertices.
A 3-cycle + 5-cycle is impossible (3+5=8 > 6).
Two 5-cycles is impossible (5+5=10 > 6).

So α₂ = #{disjoint 3-cycle pairs} at n=6.

n=6: Distribution of c₃ (number of 3-cycles):
  c₃ =  0:   720 tournaments
  c₃ =  1:   960 tournaments
  c₃ =  2:  2240 tournaments
  c₃ =  3:  2880 tournaments
  c₃ =  4:  6240 tournaments
  c₃ =  5:  3648 tournaments
  c₃ =  6:  8640 tournaments
  c₃ =  7:  4800 tournaments
  c₃ =  8:  2640 tournaments

n=6: Distribution of α₂ (disjoint 3-cycle pairs):
  α₂ = 0: 17328 tournaments
  α₂ = 1: 10880 tournaments
  α₂ = 2:  4320 tournaments
  α₂ = 4:   240 tournaments

  α₂=3 MISSING because:
  To have 3 disjoint pairs, need 3 pairs of vertex-disjoint 3-cycles.
  But each pair uses all 6 vertices in a fixed partition.
  You can only partition 6 vertices into two triples in 10 ways.
  For 3 disjoint pairs, need 3 partitions where each has both triples cyclic.
  BUT: the partitions share vertices, so cycles overlap.
  Let's count directly how many partitions can have both triples cyclic.

n=6: #{both triples cyclic' partitions:
  k = 0: 17328 tournaments
  k = 1: 10880 tournaments
  k = 2:  4320 tournaments
  k = 4:   240 tournaments

  α₂ = #both-cyclic-partitions confirmed:
  Values match: True

======================================================================
PART 5: (c₃, α₂) JOINT DISTRIBUTION AT n=6
======================================================================

  c₃ → possible α₂ values:
  c₃ =  0: α₂ ∈ [0]  (α₂=0:720)
  c₃ =  1: α₂ ∈ [0]  (α₂=0:960)
  c₃ =  2: α₂ ∈ [0, 1]  (α₂=0:2160, α₂=1:80)
  c₃ =  3: α₂ ∈ [0]  (α₂=0:2880)
  c₃ =  4: α₂ ∈ [0, 1]  (α₂=0:5520, α₂=1:720)
  c₃ =  5: α₂ ∈ [0, 1]  (α₂=0:1728, α₂=1:1920)
  c₃ =  6: α₂ ∈ [0, 1, 2]  (α₂=0:2880, α₂=1:3600, α₂=2:2160)
  c₃ =  7: α₂ ∈ [0, 1, 2]  (α₂=0:480, α₂=1:2880, α₂=2:1440)
  c₃ =  8: α₂ ∈ [1, 2, 4]  (α₂=1:1680, α₂=2:720, α₂=4:240)

  KEY: α₂=3 would require 3 partitions where BOTH triples are cyclic.
  Max α₂ = 4, achieved only when c₃ = 14 (out of max C(6,3)=20).
  The gap: no tournament has exactly 3 both-cyclic partitions.

