======================================================================
PART 7: JACOBSTHAL AND THE CORRECTION TERM
======================================================================

H + 2χ = 3 + 6α₂ + 6α₃ + 18α₄ + ...

The coefficients c_k = 2^k + 2(-1)^k for k ≥ 2:
  c_2 = 6, c_3 = 6, c_4 = 18, c_5 = 30, c_6 = 66, c_7 = 126

Do c_k satisfy the Jacobsthal recurrence c_k = c_{k-1} + 2c_{k-2}?
  c = [3, 0, 6, 6, 18, 30, 66, 126, 258, 510]
  c_2 = c_1 + 2c_0 = 0 + 6 = 6 vs actual 6: ✓
  c_3 = c_2 + 2c_1 = 6 + 0 = 6 vs actual 6: ✓
  c_4 = c_3 + 2c_2 = 6 + 12 = 18 vs actual 18: ✓
  c_5 = c_4 + 2c_3 = 18 + 12 = 30 vs actual 30: ✓
  c_6 = c_5 + 2c_4 = 30 + 36 = 66 vs actual 66: ✓
  c_7 = c_6 + 2c_5 = 66 + 60 = 126 vs actual 126: ✓
  c_8 = c_7 + 2c_6 = 126 + 132 = 258 vs actual 258: ✓

★ YES! The correction coefficients satisfy the JACOBSTHAL RECURRENCE!
  c_k = 2^k + 2(-1)^k satisfies c_k = c_{k-1} + 2c_{k-2}
  Proof: (2^{k-1}+2(-1)^{k-1}) + 2(2^{k-2}+2(-1)^{k-2})
       = 2^{k-1}+2^{k-1} + (-1)^{k-2}(−2+4) = 2^k + 2(-1)^k ✓

  These are 2× the Jacobsthal-Lucas numbers JL(k) = 2^k + (-1)^k:
  c_k = 2·JL(k) + ... no. c_k = 2^k + 2(-1)^k = 2(2^{k-1} + (-1)^k)
  For k even: c_k = 2(2^{k-1}+1), for k odd: c_k = 2(2^{k-1}-1)

  Alternative: c_k = 3·J(k+1) - J(k)?
    k=0: c_k=3, 3J(1)-J(0)=3
    k=1: c_k=0, 3J(2)-J(1)=2
    k=2: c_k=6, 3J(3)-J(2)=8
    k=3: c_k=6, 3J(4)-J(3)=12
    k=4: c_k=18, 3J(5)-J(4)=28
    k=5: c_k=30, 3J(6)-J(5)=52
    k=6: c_k=66, 3J(7)-J(6)=108
    k=7: c_k=126, 3J(8)-J(7)=212
    k=8: c_k=258, 3J(9)-J(8)=428
    k=9: c_k=510, 3J(10)-J(9)=852

======================================================================
SYNTHESIS: THE DEEP TOPOLOGY OF THE TOURNAMENT WORLD
======================================================================

1. MODULAR GROUP: M(-1) = T^(-1)S has order 6 in SL(2,Z).
   This explains period-6 at x=-1 (Euler characteristic layer).

2. MOD-3 UNIFICATION: Since 2≡-1 mod 3, the tournament matrix
   M(2) mod 3 = M(-1) mod 3. So the topological and arithmetic
   structures COINCIDE when viewed through the mod-3 lens.

3. ORDER FORMULA: order(M(2) mod p) = LCM(ord_p(2), 2).
   This equals 6 for p=3 and p=7, explaining the period-6 alignment.

4. H+2χ IDENTITY: H + 2χ = 3 + Σ_{k≥2} c_k·α_k where c_k satisfies
   the JACOBSTHAL recurrence. The correction terms are Jacobsthal-like!

5. TOPOLOGICAL PHASE TRANSITION AT n=6: 47% of tournaments have
   Ω non-complete (α₂>0). The transition is driven by the first
   appearance of vertex-disjoint 3-cycle pairs.

6. α₂=3 GAP: Due to combinatorial constraint on 3-cycle partitions.
   A tournament can have 0, 1, 2, or 4 both-cyclic partition pairs,
   but NOT 3. This is a subtle parity/symmetry effect.
